<h4 class="subsection-title">Deleting</h4>

<p>
  There are two ways to delete a module.
  You can either press on the red cross on the right of every module name or
  you can press the <code>Delete</code> button on the bottom of module edit page
  (you can press on the module name to activate a module edit page).
  <br>
  You will be asked to confirm that you really want to delete the module.
  If you confirm the module along with all lessons associated with it will be
  deleted. <strong>This is an irreversible action</strong>.
</p>

<h3 class="subtitle">Lessons</h3>

<p> Lessons are pieces of content inside of modules.</p>

<h4 class="subsection-title">Creating</h4>

<p>
  Before you create a new lesson make sure you have a module to create
  that lesson in.
  <br>
  Press on the <code>+ Lesson</code> button below the "Lessons" heading.
  This will append a new lesson to the list below the heading. Next,
  press on the lesson name (which should be "unnamed"). You will be
  presented with the details of the lesson. Initially, it will be unnamed
  and it will not a content, attachments or a summary.
</p>

<h4 class="subsection-title">Modifying</h4>

<p>
  To modify a lesson's name enter a new (or replace existing) name into
  the text box below the "Name" heading. If you'd like to change the
  summary you can do that by changing the content of the large text
  box below the "Summary" heading.
  <br>
  Uploading files requires some more explaining. We accept lesson
  content in the form of an <code>HTML</code> file. The file must not
  contain a <code>head</code> tag. It must only include the content of
  the <code>body</code> tag.
  <br>
  To upload the file press on the "choose file" button below the
  "Content" heading. Your browser should display a file picker which you
  can use to select the lesson file. Once you have uploaded a lesson file
  you may download it by clicking on the <code>Download</code> button.
  <br>
  The lessons you create may be interactive and may include images,
  audio and video. Because of that, you have the option to upload
  attachments along with the lesson file.
</p>

<p> Images need to be in one of the following formats: </p>

<ul style="list-style-type: disc;">
  <li><code>JPEG</code></li>
  <li><code>PNG</code></li>
  <li><code>GIF</code></li>
</ul>

<p>
  Audio files need to be in the <code>MP3</code> format.
</p>

<p>
  Videos need to be in either in the <code>MP4</code> or <code>MPG</code>
  formats.
</p>

<p>
  Once you are satisfied with the changes to the lesson you can click
  on the <code>Save</code> button to commit the changes.
</p>

